      "role": "user",
      "content": "i mean that's a pretty safe answer lol. but if u look at history, doesn't it seem like the \"cohesive\" part is usually just a cover for the \"dangerous\" part? like, most of the time when people start getting really nationalistic, it ends up with borders being fought over or people being treated like second-class citizens. is there actually a version of nationalism that isn't inherently problematic?",
